Employee returned to vaccination area at 13:45, reported mild intermittent tingling in hands and feet bilat; primarily feet and primarily when he sat down. Also reported mild brief blotchiness to bilat lower forearms. Narrative: Mildly anxious, mild reactions to which he was unsure if he should return to vaccination site or not. Denied dizziness, light-headedness, palpitations. Reported mild feeling of a 'rush' "kind of feeling, like, stimulated". VS: at 13:46: BP 14977. O2 99%, P 79, T 36.3. Reported he had been continuing doing his duties without difficulty but didn't know if he should be concerned. Noted blotchiness on forearms under different lighting when he went to restroom. Blotchiness mild to moderate and mostly resolved before he left. VS at 14:02: BP 136/69, O2 99%, P 80, T 36.7. Reported tingling mostly resolved if he stretches his legs out some. Reported anxiety over "the whole thing. It's just weird and I've been excited about the vaccine". Reviewed S/S to be aware of, when to seek medical attention and that he was feeling completely stable and comfortable before he left. Positively reactive to increased information and seeing improvement in blotchiness. Left at 14:08.

I had difficulty concentrating and focusing on Wednesday evening, a little over a day after getting my first shot. The focusing/concentration issues went away by the next morning when I woke up, however I have been feeling very tired physically since then. I'm yawning all day and have very little energy or interest in doing things I need to be doing. I'm not certain that this is vaccine related, and I'm not super concerned about it yet as I'm on Spring break from school, but I start virtual classes again on Monday and will be concerned if I'm still super tired. If it doesn't go away by next weekend, I will likely resubmit/add on to this report if that is an option. It is not a serious concern yet so I haven't contacted medical professionals yet, but I thought it might be a good idea to at least report that this has been going on to VAERS

Starting at 8pm on vaccination day I got loopy and disoriented, and had a hard time speaking intelligibly. I also had trouble with balance and fine motor skills. Had some personality changes too: became very moody with erratic mood swings. The next day I slept all day because of exhaustion and aches. When I woke up on Wednesday (36hrs later) I was literally screaming in pain because of how bad my arm and shoulder hurt. It hurt to move it, and hurt not to move it. It was excruciating and ibuprofen didn't seem to help at all. Throughout Wednesday I could hardly move my left arm. Getting dressed or washing my hair was very difficult and very painful. I was also still very uncoordinated. My left armpits lymph nodes were so swollen that (1) it filled in my entire armpit so there was no more pit, just a very soft bulge, and (2) the fluid extended all the way to my chest and it looked like I had one breast and one pec.

Close
Vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights; Vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights; light headiness a feeling that i would pass out or die and tingling and shakimg; tingling and shaking throughout his body; tingling and shaking throughout his body; As he remained in a confused mental state; received bnt162b2 first dose on 10Mar2021, second dose on 24Mar2021; received bnt162b2 first dose on 10Mar2021, second dose on 24Mar2021; nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger; Occasinally elevated blood pressure; slight markings of dehydration; hangover; This is a spontaneous report from a Contactable consumer (patient). A 40-year-old male patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, brand: Pfizer), second dose via an unspecified route of administration, administered in arm left on 24Mar2021 11:30 at age of 40-year-old (Lot Number: ER8733) at single dose for COVID-19 immunization. The most recent COVID-19 vaccine was administered at Facility of Doctor's office/urgent care. Medical history included gout, anxiety, gastrooesophageal reflux disease, 'espoghutis'. The patient did not have allergies to medications, food, or other products. Concomitant medication within 2 weeks of vaccination included omeprazole; allopurinol; escitalopram. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The patient previously took first dose of bnt162b2 via an unspecified route of administration, administered in arm left on 10Mar2021 11:30 at age of 40-year-old (Lot Number: En6206) at single dose for COVID-19 immunization. On 02Apr2021, the patient had vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights and unusual feelings as he initially fell asleep. He was able to wake himself up but remained in between sleep and awake. This was accompanied by light headiness a feeling that he would pass out or die and tingling and shaking throughout his body as he remained in a confused mental state while his wife called an ambulance. In 2021, his vitals were fine with occasionally elevated blood pressure and slight markings of dehydration ( during the day following his second dose he felt like he had a bad hangover). The ER doctor thought the most likely explanation is sometime of nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger. He had not previously sufferer anything like it. The events were reported as non-serious. The adverse events result in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and emergency room/department or urgent care. The patient received treatment for the adverse events which included: drugs to calm, fluids. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The outcome of the events light headiness, tingling and shaking throughout his body, confused mental state, nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger, vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights, elevated blood pressure, slight markings of dehydration, hangover were resolving. Information on lot/batch number obtained. Further information is expected.

Patient DOB: 11/18/1980. Received his first dose Pfizer (LOT#: EW0179 EXP: 8/2021) at 1108 on 4/27/21. Patient alerted EMT. Patient stated that she was sweating a lot and felt like his vision went blurry/dark for about 3 minutes. Patient stated that he also felt nervous. EMT alerted PHN. BP: 118/60, pulse: 65, O2: 97%. Patient was given water. PHN recommended that patient stay an extra 30 minutes. Patient agreed. EMT re-assessed patient. Patient stated that he was feeling a lot better and that his vision was completely fine now. Patient left vaccination site unassisted and with a steady gait at 1150.

The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination, and had not been tested post-vaccination. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.

41 2021-05-09 impaired work ability On April 18 and 19, following my 2nd injection, I had very bad chills and could not get warm. I was ... Read more
Close
On April 18 and 19, following my 2nd injection, I had very bad chills and could not get warm. I was nauseous although I did not vomit. On April 22, I began having severe sharp stabbing pains just to the right of my belly button. It felt like I was being stabbed with a very hot knife, and after about 15-90 seconds, it would go away. Anytime I reached for something, bent over, twisted, turned or tried to hug someone, I would get this same pain and it would double me over in pain. On Monday April 26 at 7pm, I finally checked into the Emergency Room at the direction of my Primary Doctor. They did a bunch of blood work on me and sent me for a CT Scan of my abdomen. All of the blood work came back in normal ranges, and the CT Scan showed my appendix was "borderline" according to the surgeon. They consulted with Dr and decided to admit me for a surgical consult and further examination. They gave me fluids and morphine through an IV for the first 24 - 36 hrs, and then switched to Norco by mouth. I continued having pain throughout my stay. On Thursday, April 29, they took me to surgery for "exploratory surgery" with the intention of removing my appendix and looking around to see if anything else stood out to them that would cause me this pain. They stated my appendix had scar tissue on it and they removed it, but said they did not know if this would stop the pain I was having. On Friday April 30, I was released from the hospital at approximately 6pm. By 9pm on Friday, I began having those same sharp, stabbing, burning pains in my abdomen again, now to the right of my belly button again and further towards my right side. I also had sharp burning pain in the inside of my upper right arm, between my bicep and tricep muscles. This pain continued on through the weekend occurring more frequently and more severe. On Monday morning at about 1:30am, I woke up with severe abdominal pains all over and went into the bathroom. I had diarrhea and nausea and felt like I was going to vomit. Between 1:30am and 7:30am, I went to the bathroom 6 times. I went to work on Monday and continued having abdominal pains and diarrhea all day and night. On Tuesday, I went to the bathroom a total of 17 times. On Wednesday, I saw my primary Dr., who examined my abdomen and pains. He suggested I take immodium for the diarrhea and a supplement for muscle pain, as he felt this was the cause of my pain. On Wednesday, I went to the bathroom 21 times and was very nauseaus. I started the Imodium and it had no effect on me whatsoever. On Thursday, I had to call off work because I couldn't stop using the bathroom. By 4pm, I had been to the bathroom 18 times. I returned to the ER. They took a stool sample and did an ultrasound in the ER. They decided to admit me again for surgical consult and pain management. On Friday, Dr ordered another ultrasound of my abdomen, specifically my gallbladder, kidney, and liver. He also sent me for a CT Scan with contrast. They completed a total lab workup of my blood. All of these results came back normal, and nothing on the images showed anything wrong with my organs. On Saturday May 8, Dr came to the hospital to examine me. He stated everything related to my GI was fine. He asked if I have back pain, which I told him I do. At this time, I was in extreme pain and I couldn't even touch my skin. Dr attempted to examine my abdomen, and just by placing his hand on my stomach, I screamed in pain. He then put his hand behind my back and pushed a little, and it cause extreme pain in my abdomen. At this time, Dr suggested that maybe the pain is caused by something going on in my back. Maybe a pinched nerve or something. He ordered an X-ray of my upper and lower spine. Later that day, the results of the X-ray came back and showed there was nothing wrong with my spine. With these results, Dr then ordered an MRI of my lumbar and thoracic spine. On Sunday May 9 at 1030am, I was taken to radiology for an MRI. The initial report shows that I do not have any pinched nerves and nothing notable that would cause this type of pain in my body. As of now, no diagnosis or explanation for the pain I am experiencing. The pain is gradually getting worse and at times I am unable to move at all without extreme severe pain in my body. At times, my right groin hurts and I am unable to stand on my feet, as it feels as if I have pulled a groin muscle. The pain in my abdomen takes my breath away and feels like I am being set on fire in that area of my body. The pain no longer goes away and is constant, but moves throughout my right side from my groin to my shoulder only. I am not able to put my right arm behind my back because I get this pain in the back of my shoulder area. This pain is only on my right side at this time. So far, there is no explanation for this pain. I never had anything like this until I got the vaccine.

Then on about the 5th day after, my lower back pain increased, causing significant sciatic pain worse than ever before. On 22JAN21 I ended up going to urgent care for increased breathing problems, and also had to have pain management appointment within days as sciatic pain was debilitating and also significantly interfered with my sleep. After steroid injection (In spine)on FEB 3rd for sciatica/back pain, and steroids/inhaler treatment for the breathing stuff, I would say I was pretty good to go . I didn't think too much of these unusual events for me both in timing and severity. On 12FEB2021, I got my second pfizer covid dose. I 14FEB I started noticing allergy symptoms again, and slight shortness of breath, used inhaler I had from before to help as breathing in seemed to not give me full breaths. Then, on 15FEB2021, in the evening out of nowhere while walking, my lower back/sciatica pain came back in full force, as if my leg were a lighting rod like before. So it almost seems as if the covid vaccine triggered an inflammatory reaction in my body. I am not certain, but because the series of events seem the same and in timing after my first covid vaccine, I figured I would at least report it.

She prescribed Baclofen 10 mg and took me off the Cephalexin and put me on Amoxycillin because we thought the problem might have been an ear infection. The next week I spoke with my Primary Care Physician, and he believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia, so he put me on Carbamazepine 200 mg twice a day. That same week, on April 9, I was finally able to meet with the Physician Assistant at the Neurologists office and she also believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia. I continued to take the Carbamazepine daily and the Baclofen and Oxycodone-Acetaminophen as needed. On Monday April 12 I informed the nurses at the Neurologist office that I was experiencing several symptoms/side effects that included dizziness, weakness, difficulty swallowing and a pounding heartbeat. The nurses talked with the PA and the PA took me off the Carbamazepine and put me on Oxcarbazepine 150 mg twice a day and she prescribed Methylprednisolone 4 mg. On Thursday April 15 I began to have intense prolonged pain behind my left ear down to the neck and in the Trigeminal nerves in the forehead and top of the head on the left side. I was in so much pain I slept for less than 2 hours. The next morning, I vomited and went to the Emergency Room again. At the ER they treated my pain with a headache IV cocktail that included Ibuprofen, Benadryl, an anti-nausea medication, Fentanyl, and a steroid. Within an hour my pain level dropped from a 9 to a 3 and I was released. The ER prescribed Gabapentin 300 mg (3 times a day) which I started the evening of April 16. I have had less constant pain since leaving the ER and starting the Gabapentin, but I continue to have pain in the Trigeminal nerve areas and neck with some flare ups that reach a 7 out of 10 in pain. I am scheduled for an MRI on April 23 and a visit with the Neurologist on May 10.

Close
Some background: I normally react badly to flu/respiratory vaccines in that I generally get sicker after the vaccine than I do when I get the virus. So this isn't entirely unexpected. However, the timing is really strange and Now I wonder if I should get COVID tested. Here is the chronology of events. Day of shot (Friday) - pain in arm lasted about 2 days but wasn't too intense. As the pain in the arm began to fade, I started getting really sleepy. I slept probably 48 hours over the next three days but did not experience any pain except maybe slight muscle aches and a little of the accompanying eye burn that is associated muscle aches and sleepiness. By Tuesday, the sleepiness had passed. Thursday night (last night), I started to experience ALL general symptoms of a respiratory flu/COVID. I developed an intense cough and associated phlem (though it is very sporadic rather than persistent) and the precursors to intense muscle pain. I woke up at around 3am Friday with a fever, the muscle pain, burning eyes (associated with flu-muscle pain and fever), and extreme chills (though my windows was open... a normal practice as my computer makes it hot in my room). I felt oddly rested however, as though the getting sick, while making me tired, was also helping me sleep better. My body is definitely reacting to something. If it wasn't 6 days afterward, I would say it was my normal reaction to virus shots. However, the timing is alarming. I have not knowingly been exposed to anyone with COVID. This morning the chills are gone, the fever is down (though not entirely gone), but I still feel "down for the count." Like I said... it is my normal reaction to virus vaccine except that it is about 6 days late (usually sets in within 24 hours). This morning is the week "anniversary" of the shot.

49 2021-03-01 abnormal behaviour Early Wednesday morning (2/24) around 5:00AM, I woke up to extreme pain in my left arm, primarily al... Read more
Close
Early Wednesday morning (2/24) around 5:00AM, I woke up to extreme pain in my left arm, primarily along the upper forearm, inside of my elbow, and lower bicep. There was no trauma or unusual behavior prior to onset of pain. It came on suddenly and worsened with extension of the arm. Symptoms worsened over the next few days, with pain intensifying and extending down into my hand and up into my armpit and shoulder. I tried ice, Ibuprofen, Acetaminophen, and Vicodin for pain relief, but nothing really helped other than the ice. On Saturday morning (2/27), I visited Urgent Care and was diagnosed as brachial plexis neuritis, aka Parsonage-Turner Syndrome by Dr and prescribed Prednisone and rest. On Sunday evening (2/28), I went to the ER seeking pain relief and second opinion. On Monday (3/1) morning, I was seen by ED doctors, and then three different neurologists. After doing an ultrasound which ruled out vein/artery thrombosis, the neuro team diagnosed Parsonage-Turner Syndrome. They've prescribed Gabapentin, Acetaminophen, and Ibuprofen for pain relief, a follow-up neuro consult, an MRI for next Friday, and an EMG in a few weeks. Last night while sitting and reading, the same pain began in my right arm, similarly to how it presented in my left arm last week. The right arm pain is less than the left arm pain, but at this point seven days later, I am experiencing neuropathic pain in both arms.

However, a week or so in his usual daily activities started slowing down (e.g., going from daily showers to 3 times a week, not getting chores done in a timely manner). On 04/27/21, he got his second shot, resulting in complete mental shutdown. Patient was not showering or shaving and only ate when forced. All internal sense of motivation and intuition was gone. He experienced memory issues, trouble speaking, and suffered from a ?complete state of nothingness which I?ve never experienced before? also known as abulia. He rarely took part in activities he did daily before the vaccine such as spending time on PC and reading the news. On 5/16/21, his condition started to improve and his precious feelings of "nothingness" turned to anger. He got intense neuropathy escalation in fingertips at this time which lasted about a week and half. His reaction lasted two months and now he is currently able to shower, shave, and exercise daily but still has memory and executive functioning issues.

Within approximately a couple of days from the first of two COVID19 Pfizer injections, I developed a progressive, systemic, neuro/neuro-muscular inflammatory pain response. The inflammation and pain first manifested in my left wrist and hand, greatly worsening recent symptomology that may have been the start of a carpal tunnel syndrome. The inflammation and pain then progressed to my right wrist and hand and right shoulder. Then they progressed to my left shoulder, under my clavicles, my hips, and my upper lumbar/lower thoracic region of my spine. Muscle groups tightened and hurt, chief among them my hamstrings and upper back. All within days. The inflammation and pain were severe, especially from the early a.m. (3 or 4 in the a.m.) to waking hours. And the conditions left me nearly debilitated and incapable of sleeping well or performing many ADLs. Then, on Monday, March 29, 2021, I saw an orthopaedic for the pains in my wrists and hands, and he prescribed me a steroid for a preliminary diagnose of bilateral carpal tunnel. The inflammation and pain throughout my body decreased considerably after only two doses of the steroids. That led me to seek a consultation with the rheumatologist.

Within 5-minutes of vaccination, the patient reported weakness and confusion. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. No signs of stroke. EKG demonstrated NSR, rate 77bpm, no ST elevation. FSBG was 290mg/dl. EMS transported the patient to Hospital Emergency Department. Enroute, the patient became increasingly confused, forgetting their birthday and location. Patient was hypertensive (178/104) and reported a "crushing headache". EMS crew became concerned for stroke. In ED, the patient remained hypertensive (178/93). ED Physician had high suspicion of TIA versus acute reaction to COVID-19 vaccine. Administerd 650mg acetaminophen and 1mg Lorazepam. Admitted patient to critical care unit where patient stated they had developed a sudden-onset diffuse banding-like headache with associated nausea, diaphoresis, blurry vision, and confusion. MRI was negative and patient was transferred from ICU to hospital. Hospital physician believed the symptoms were likely a vagal mediated response or reaction to his COVID vaccination. Patient was discharged on 3/20 with diagnoses of TIA, Acute encephalopathy, Insulin-dependent type 2 diabetes, Essential hypertension, CAD, Unspecified mood disorder, Dyslipidemia, Obesity, and Mild neuro cognitive disorder

Nurse received a brief report from the vaccinator, and then walked over to the vaccination station to talk to the client. The client explained to Nurse that he received his first dose on his left arm and about 2 days later, he developed "numbness and tingling" in that same arm and it has not resolved. As Nurse asked further questions, she discovered that the client also started to develop that same sensation, of numbness and tingling, in his right hand. The client described that it is painful, if poked in those areas. Client denied any known drug allergies as well as denied any past medical history. He stated he had his left index finger amputated "years ago, but that is it." Nurse explained to the client that there are some concerns regarding the new onset of symptoms after receiving the vaccine and that she would like to get a medical consult before deciding how to proceed with the second dose. Client agreed. Nurse sent a text message for a medical consult received an answer about 45 minutes later. The medical team recommended waiting to give the second dose until the client is assessed by either a primary care provider or neurologist. They also gave the client the option of receiving the JOHNSON and JOHNSON vaccine 28 days after the first dose, if the client does not wish to receive PFIZER again. Nurse then educated the client on the recommendations. The client expressed to Nurse that he is "very healthy and does not go anywhere," so he does not wish to be seen by a medical provider right now. The client asked questions regarding vaccine efficacy in the first and second doses and Nurse addressed them. The client told Nurse that at this time, he would like to hold off on getting a medical assessment and did not wish to reschedule for a JOHNSON and JOHNSON vaccine. Nurse respectfully acknowledged his decision and educated him on V- safe and how to proceed if he changes his mind later down the road.

On 2/19/2021, I decided to seek medical care for my constipation, stomach cramps, fatigue, difficulty concentrating and shortness of breath. The doctor diagnosed me with Covid long hauler (I had a previous covid infection in 11/2020). I was prescribe probotics (for constipation) and rest for 2 months. I am still feeling fatigue and having heart palpitations. They order ECG(normal) and blood work (normal).
